From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: MeshCore Security Audit <audit@meshcore.local>
Date: Thu, 24 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/4] bug22: Add brownout detection with deferred flash writes

The nRF52840 POWER peripheral has a power-failure comparator (POF) that
generates an event when VDD drops below a configurable threshold.

This patch:
1. Enables the POF comparator at 2.4V threshold in NRF52Board::begin()
2. Polls EVENTS_POFWARN each loop() iteration via board.checkBrownout()
3. Adds MainBoard::brownoutDetected() virtual (default: false)
4. Overrides brownoutDetected() in NRF52Board using the hardware flag
5. Guards savePrefs() — if brownoutDetected(), sets a pending flag
   instead of writing. The pending save is flushed in loop() once
   voltage recovers.
6. Guards saveRegions() the same way via a separate pending flag
7. Guards acl.save() — defers dirty_contacts_expiry by 200ms

The prefs are already updated in RAM by the set command. Only the flash
write is deferred. Once voltage recovers, loop() detects the pending
flag and flushes to flash automatically — no data is lost.

The POF comparator uses direct register access (no SoftDevice dependency).
2.4V threshold is well above the 1.7V flash minimum, giving margin for
the voltage regulator and transient sag during LoRa TX.

The POF event is edge-triggered (fires on VDD falling below threshold).
Recovery is detected by polling getBattMilliVolts() via ADC roughly once
per hour (not every loop), requiring VDD > 2.6V (200mV hysteresis).
When recovery is confirmed, the POF event is cleared and pending saves
are flushed automatically.
